    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nClick functions in statuscolumn don't respect `minwid`  first argument that can be different per line.\n\nAs per the `:help 'statuscolumn'`:\n\n```\nNOTE: The %@ click execute function item is supported as well but the\nspecified function will be the same for each row in the same column.\nIt cannot be switched out through a dynamic 'statuscolumn' format, the\nhandler should be written with this in mind.\n```\n\nEven if the \"click\" function is the same, it is executed with the `minwid` first argument that acts the same across all lines, even including its \"clickable ranges\".\n\n---\n\nThe original use case for this issue is to be able to act differently on virtual, wrapped, and non-wrapped lines. Currently it doesn't seem to be possible (without hacking on `getmousepos` output). Since `v:virtnum` is not available at the time of click handler execution while this issue shows that there is no way to pass information about the current line type to the handler.\n\n---\n\nProbably related/relevant to #21767. @luukvbaal\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create the following 'init.lua':\n\n    ```lua\n    -- Define statuscolumn with clickable ranges\n    _G.log = {}\n    _G.click = function(minwid) table.insert(_G.log, minwid) end\n\n    _G.statuscol = function()\n      if vim.v.lnum == 1 then return '%1@v:lua.click@one%X %2@v:lua.click@ONE%X' end\n      return '%3@v:lua.click@two%X %4@v:lua.click@TWO%X'\n    end\n    vim.o.statuscolumn = '%{%v:lua.statuscol()%}'\n\n    vim.api.nvim_buf_set_lines(0, 0, -1, false, { '', '', '' })\n    vim.bo.modified = false\n    ```\n\n2. `nvim --clean -u init.lua`\n3. Click on the following words in the statuscolumn: `one`, `ONE`, `two`, `TWO`.\n4. `:=log`. It shows `{ 1, 2, 1, 2 }`, meaning that all clicks were executed as if in the first line. The expected log is `{ 1, 2, 3, 4 }`.\n\n---\n\nFor reference, here is the 'init.lua' for the more useful case of being able to tell if the click happens inside non-wrarpped, virtual, or wrapped line (clicking on all different words act as clicking on `text` or `TEXT`):\n\n```lua\n-- Define statuscolumn with clickable ranges\n_G.log = {}\n_G.click = function(minwid) table.insert(_G.log, minwid) end\n\n_G.statuscol = function()\n  -- Create three types of statuscolumn lines with two clickable ranges:\n  -- - Non-wrapped: `text TEXT`, `text` click 1, `TEXT` - 2\n  -- - Virtual:     `virt VIRT`, `virt` click 3, `VIRT` - 4\n  -- - Wrapped:     `wrap WRAP`, `wrap` click 5, `WRAP` - 6\n  local ltype = vim.v.virtnum == 0 and 'text' or (vim.v.virtnum < 0 and 'virt' or 'wrap')\n  local minwid = vim.v.lnum == 2 and 7 or (ltype == 'text' and 1 or (ltype == 'virt' and 3 or 5))\n  return string.format('%%%d@v:lua.click@%s%%X %%%d@v:lua.click@%s%%X', minwid, ltype, minwid + 1, ltype:upper())\nend\nvim.o.statuscolumn = '%{%v:lua.statuscol()%}'\n\n-- Set buffer with long line to show text+virtual+wrapped lines\nlocal buf_id = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(true, false)\nvim.api.nvim_buf_set_lines(buf_id, 0, -1, false, { '', '', string.rep('a', 3 * vim.o.columns) })\nlocal ns_id = vim.api.nvim_create_namespace('test')\nlocal extmark_opts = { virt_lines_above = true, virt_lines = { { { 'Virtual line', 'String' } } } }\nvim.api.nvim_buf_set_extmark(buf_id, ns_id, 2, 0, extmark_opts)\nvim.bo[buf_id].modified = false\n\nvim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(buf_id)\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nOne of:\n1. Each 'statuscolumn' line (even generated) is allowed to have arbitrary mouse click handlers.\n2. Each 'statuscolumn' line (even generated) is allowed to call the same mouse click handler with different `minwid` argument.\n3. Be able to *easily* get during mouse click handler execution the values of `v:lnum` and `v:virtnum`.\n\nIf all of the above is absolutely impossible, then as full documentation about mouse click limitations as possible would go a long way. Like \"it only acts based on the top line format in the window column; including handlers, their `minwid` / `maxwid` arguments, and ranges\". Which is very limiting, in my opinion.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-692+g3ed78daf83\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, doesn't have this functionality\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 7.0.11-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.3.1-arch2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppimage",
