            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> What do you want to have happen differently when clicking a normal/wrapped/virtual part of the statuscolumn? \n\nSome example after quick brainstorm:\n- Hide virtual line(s).\n- Unwrap all lines/\n- Yank text of the clicked virtual line.\n- Yank wrapped portion of the text line.\n\n> A user supposedly clicks on text/signs in the statuscolumn. What is clicked can be determined with `screenstring(getmouspos()...)` in the click handler callback.\n\nThis assumes that clicked text is enough to get all the information. It might be enough for regular lines, but might not be enough for virtual and wrapped lines. Like if all of them are shown as placeholder text (`V` for virtual line and `W` for wrapped line, for example).\n\n> I still don't really think the cost of maintaining a possibly `win_height * <statuscol_width>` store of click handlers is reasonable/worth the trouble.\n\nI am not sure what \"click handlers\" here means. My guess is that this is an internal way of deciding what to do after the click and is stored per cell.\n\nAlthough it does sound like a more memory requirement, the current limitation is very implementation related, limits what can be done with 'statuscolumn', and not very obvious. For example, after reading documentation I assumed that it means that there can only be one `%@MyClick@` function, which is probably not the case.\n\nIf the memory footprint is the concern here, then maybe it is feasible to store extra click information for lines that have different \"click range arrangement\" (for lack of better terms). Similar to how screenshot tests here handle repeating lines: collapse repeating but show in full different lines.",
