            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Another use case that this implementation detail affects is when wanting to display text content only for parts of the window. Like only current line or skip some sections on non-current line. For example:\n\n```lua\n-- Define statuscolumn with clickable ranges\n_G.log = {}\n_G.click = function(minwid) table.insert(_G.log, minwid) end\n\n_G.statuscol = function()\n  if vim.v.lnum == vim.api.nvim_win_get_cursor(0)[1] then return '%=%1@v:lua.click@%l%X %2@v:lua.click@sep%X' end\n  return '%=%2@v:lua.click@sep%X'\nend\nvim.o.statuscolumn = '%{%v:lua.statuscol()%}'\n\nvim.o.number = true\nlocal redraw_stc = function() vim.api.nvim__redraw({ win = 0, statuscolumn = true }) end\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('CursorMoved', { callback = redraw_stc })\n\nvim.api.nvim_buf_set_lines(0, 0, -1, false, { '', '', '' })\nvim.bo.modified = false\n```\n\nWhen cursor is at the top visible line, clicking on the line number adds to the `_G.log`. But when cursor is lower, nothing happens.\n\n---\n\nThere is a hacky workaround to use custom \"hide\" (`:hi Hide guifg=bg gui=nocombine`) and \"reset\" (`:hi Reset gui=nocombine`) highlight groups, but I couldn't make it work reliably (like the `%s` for signs still shows highlighted signs).",
